Introduction
Trainees in hospice and palliative medicine bear witness to the full range of human emotions while caring for patients with serious illness. While there have been efforts to incorporate arts and humanities into medical education, most hospice and palliative medicine fellowship curricula only include one-time experiences, and few curricula to date engage with art forms beyond the written word and/or incorporate expertise from practitioners outside of medicine. We hypothesized that integrating the humanities into the formal curriculum would enhance coping skills and would grant fellows space to be more reflective, analytical, and empathetic. The Arts and Ethics curriculum was created to train fellows with necessary skills in humanism, ethics, and burnout prevention.
Methods
